      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm working on my dissertation data and i'm a bit stuck. i have a result where the p-value is 0.06. it looks like there is a clear trend in the graph, but my advisor is saying it's not statistically significant. can you explain the technical reason why 0.06 fails the standard threshold even if the effect looks real? like, why does that extra 0.01 matter so much?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, when the standard threshold is set at 0.05, is just a little too high, leading to the \"not statistically significant\" verdict. This is a classic case of a small, slightly-too-weak signal being drowned out by the noise, or perhaps, the actual effect size is just too small to be considered a real, robust finding. It's like trying to find a single, perfectly ripe piece of fruit in a giant pile of rotten ones—you see a trend, but you can't prove it's *the* fruit.\n\nThe technical reason is rooted in the concept of the significance level ($\\alpha$). When you set $\\alpha = 0.05$, you are essentially saying you are willing to accept a 5% chance of making a Type I error—that is, concluding there *is* an effect when, in reality, there isn't one (a false positive). A p-value of 0.06 means there is a 6% chance of seeing your data (or more extreme data) if the null hypothesis were actually true. Since 6% is greater than your 5% tolerance, you fail",
      "source": "target",
